DENGUE - NEW CALEDONIA & COOK ISLANDS: DATA
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Dengue - New Caledonia (02) 980217183320
Dengue - Cook Islands 980317234831
Dengue - Cook Islands (02) 980325232605
Date: Thu, 07 May 1998 20:26:17 -0600
From: Charles H. Calisher <calisher@usa.healthnet.org>

Steve Berger has abstracted, from the GIDEON software program, the
following historical background on dengue in New Caledonia and Cook Islands.
New Caledonia:
- Dengue outbreaks were reported in 1908, 1926, and 1943 to 1944. An
epidemic during 1971 to 1972 involved at least 40% of the population.
- 66 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) were reported during 1975 to
1979; 160 during 1980 to 1984; 662 during 1985 to 1989; 119 during 1990 to
1993.
- No cases of dengue were reported in 1978. In 1979, an outbreak involved
11% of persons on Thio (Noumea), with 5 cases of DHF (only 118 cases were
officially reported from New Caledonia that year).
- An estimated 25,000 were infected during an outbreak in 1989.
- 1,820 cases (563 of these in Noumea) including 37 DHF were confirmed
during January to June 1995 - 60% from Southern Province and 40% from
Northern Province.
- 243 cases were reported in 1997; 347 during January to February 1998 -
36% from Ouvea (Loyalty Islands) and 23% from Noumea.

Cook Islands:
- A large outbreak (254 registered; 2,000 estimated) was reported in 1976.

- 357 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) were reported during 1980 to
1984; 5 during 1985 to 1989; 1,494 during 1990 to 1993.
- 833 cases (531 from Rarotonga) were reported during an outbreak in 1991.
- 779 cases were reported during February to July 1995 - 75% of these
occurred on Rarotonga, with isolated reports from Mauke and Penrhyn.

- 123 cases (39 hospitalized) were reported for Rarotonga during January to
February 1997 - 1,075 clinical cases (0 fatal) during December 1996 to June
1997.
